First, apply matrix completion to data using the softImpute package, which provides a very eicient implementation of a generalization of algorithm 12.1 in Book (An Introduction to Statistical Learning)

# Create data frame without id
df <- my_data_unique[,-1]

# Convert the dataframe to a matrix (softImpute works with matrices)
matrix_data <- as.matrix(df)

# Perform matrix completion using softImpute
imputed_matrix <- softImpute(matrix_data)

# Access the completed matrix (imputed values)
completed_matrix <- imputed_matrix$u %*% diag(imputed_matrix$d) %*% t(imputed_matrix$v)

# Convert the completed matrix back to a dataframe
imputed_df <- as.data.frame(completed_matrix)
colnames(imputed_df) <- colnames(df) # Preserve column names

# Check for missing values again
colSums(is.na(imputed_df))
## col1 col2 col3 col4 col5 col6 
##    0    0    0    0    0    0

Second, give missing values in id column temporary sample names.

Perform K-means clusteringr in pricipal components

First briefly examine the data.

apply(my_data_cleaned[,-1] , 2, mean)
##       col1       col2       col3       col4       col5       col6 
## -0.5145648  0.7118292 82.9789934 25.8972349 -0.1780429 82.9806033

Notice that the variables have vastly different means.

apply(my_data_cleaned[,-1] , 2, var)
##         col1         col2         col3         col4         col5         col6 
## 5.620875e-01 9.908611e-02 9.534890e+02 1.629147e+03 4.203552e-03 9.537521e+02

the variables also have vastly different variances.

We have to scale the data, because PCA is sensitive to the variances of the original variables. If variables have significantly different scales, the variables with larger variances will dominate the PCA process.

# Select numeric variables
df<- my_data_cleaned[, -1]

# Perform PCA with scaled data
pr.out <- prcomp(df , scale = TRUE)

#variance explained by each principal component
pr.var <- pr.out$sdev ^2
pr.var
## [1] 3.790689e+00 2.209311e+00 7.526176e-29 1.259614e-30 7.605732e-31
## [6] 3.539482e-32

Compute the proportion of variance explained by each principal component, divide the variance explained by each principal component by the total variance explained by all 6 principal components:

# proportion of variance explained by each principal component
pve <- pr.var / sum(pr.var)
pve
## [1] 6.317816e-01 3.682184e-01 1.254363e-29 2.099356e-31 1.267622e-31
## [6] 5.899136e-33
# plot results
par(mfrow = c(1, 2))

plot(pve , xlab = " Principal Component ", ylab = " Proportion of Variance Explained ", ylim = c(0, 1), type = "b")

plot(cumsum(pve), xlab = " Principal Component ", ylab = " Cumulative Proportion of Variance Explained ", ylim = c(0, 1), type = "b")


We see that the first principal component explains 63.2 % of the variance in the data, the next principal component explains 36.8 % of the variance, and so forth. PCA help reduce dimentions.


We then use first 2 components for k-mean clustering:

# Extract the first two principal components
pcs <- pr.out$x[, 1:2]

# K-means clustering for first two principal components
# K = 2
kmeans_result <- kmeans(pcs, centers = 2)

# Plot clusters
plot(pcs[, 1], pcs[, 2], col = kmeans_result$cluster, pch = 19, xlab = "Principal Component 1", ylab = "Principal Component 2", main = "K-Means Clustering Results with first 2 components")
legend("topright", legend = unique(kmeans_result$cluster), col = unique(kmeans_result$cluster), pch = 19)


k-means clustering assigns data points to clusters and updates the cluster centroids to minimize the distance between data points and their respective cluster centers.

Reshape data frame (MAS202M_2025_proteomics_measurements_20250313), use subject_id as rows and Assay(protein) as column:

data <- MAS202M_2025_proteomics_measurements_20250313

# Get unique subject IDs and Assays(Protein)
subject_ids <- unique(data$subject_id)
assays <- unique(data$Assay)

# Create an empty data frame to store the reshaped data
reshaped_data <- data.frame(subject_id = subject_ids)

# Loop through each Assay and add it as a column
for (assay in assays) {
  reshaped_data[[assay]] <- NA # Initialize the column with NA values
  for (i in 1:nrow(reshaped_data)) {
    subject_id <- reshaped_data$subject_id[i]
    # Find the corresponding NPX value for the subject_id and Assay
    npx_value <- data$NPX[data$subject_id == subject_id & data$Assay == assay]
    if (length(npx_value) > 0) {
      reshaped_data[[assay]][i] <- npx_value[1] # Assign the first matching value
    }
  }
}
# check reshaped_data dimention

Goal Pick a quantitative variable (CD38) in the data set. Build a regression for the variable using two different methods. Use the models for prediction. One models for linear regression, the other for non-linear relationships between dimensions. Tune the parameters of each regression model and compare their performances. Discuss the outcome, including the strengths and weaknesses of each type of regression model relative to the data set. What (if anything) can we infer about the structure of the data from the models.

We use variables (NPX values in proteins, age, BMI and COVID index) in the data set to predict NPX value (quantitative variable) in protein CD38

Ridge Regression

Strengths of Ridge Regression:
Use lambda () as a Regularization Parameter. A larger lambda value leads to greater shrinkage, meaning the coefficients are pushed closer to zero. This shrinkage helps to prevent overfitting, particularly when we have many predictors or when predictors are highly correlated (multicollinearity).

Weaknesses of Ridge Regression:
Doesnt perform feature selection, all predictors will be used in the model.

# remove subject_id from data set
df <- merge_df[,-1]

# split data to train and test data
# 2 methods will use same train and test data for comparison
set.seed (1)
train <- sample (1: nrow(df), nrow(df) / 2)
# Ridge Regression use glmnet()

# Prepare the data for glmnet (glmnet needs a matrix of predictors)
# Remove intercept
x <- model.matrix(CD38 ~ ., data = df[train,])[, -1] 
y <- df[train,]$CD38

# Cross-validation for Ridge (alpha = 0 for Ridge, 10-fold CV)
set.seed(1)
ridge_cv <- cv.glmnet(x, y, alpha = 0, nfolds = 10)
plot(ridge_cv)

# Best lambda from cross-validation
best_lambda_ridge <- ridge_cv$lambda.min
cat('Best lambda:', best_lambda_ridge, '\n')
## Best lambda: 0.56557
# Ridge model with best lambda
ridge_model <- glmnet(x, y, alpha = 0, lambda = best_lambda_ridge)
# Predictions
x <- model.matrix(CD38 ~ ., data = df[-train,])[, -1]
y <- df[-train,]$CD38

ridge_predictions <- predict(ridge_model, newx = x)

# Performance evaluation (MSE)
ridge_mse <- mean((ridge_predictions - y)^2)
cat("test data MSE (Ridge Regression):", ridge_mse)
## test data MSE (Ridge Regression): 0.09507384

Plot the predicted values from Ridge model against the actual target values.

plot(ridge_predictions, y, xlab = "Prediction value", ylab = "NPX value", main = "Predicted vs. Actual Plots (Ridge Regression)")
abline(0, 1, col = "red")

Bagging (Random Forests)

bagging is a special case of a random forest with m = p.
p represents the total number of predictors (or features) in the dataset.
m represents the number of predictors randomly selected at each split when building a decision tree within the random forest.

Strengths:
Random forests provide a measure of feature importance, allowing to identify the most influential variables in the model.

Weakness:
Random forests are less interpretable. Training a large number of trees can be computationally expensive, especially with large datasets.

# bagging m = p
n<- ncol(df)-1

set.seed(1)
bag<- randomForest(CD38~., data = df, subset = train, mtry = n, importance = TRUE)
bag

ntree determines how many individual decision trees the random forest will construct. Generally, a larger ntree leads to more stable and reliable results.

# tune parameter ntree = 1000

Both methods use all variables to predict CD38. The results indicates that Ridge Regression performed better than Bagging on the test set. It suggests that the relationship between predictors and the target variable (CD38) is more likely to be linear or non-linearities are weak or absent.
The small difference (0.03) in test set error suggests that while linearity is a good fit, there might be some non-linearities or complexities in the data that bagging could potentially capture.

We use NPX values in proteins, age and BMI to predict if a person has COVID or not. (categorical variable = COVID)

Lasso regression

Lassos primary strength is its ability to perform feature selection by shrinking the coefficients of less important variables to zero. Lasso regression helps to avoid overfitting.

After a lasso logistic regression is run, a threshold is needed to turn the predicted probabilities into classifications. The chosen threshold has a large impact on the confusion matrix (result).

# Create model matrix
x <- model.matrix(COVID ~ ., data = df[train,])[, -1] # remove intercept
y <- as.factor(df[train,]$COVID)

# Cross-validation to find optimal lambda
cv_lasso <- cv.glmnet(x, y, alpha = 1, family = "binomial")
best_lambda <- cv_lasso$lambda.min
cat('lambda:', best_lambda, '\n')
## lambda: 0.02134997
# Train Lasso logistic regression model with optimal lambda
lasso_model_best <- glmnet(x, y, alpha = 1, family = "binomial", lambda = best_lambda)
# Make predictions
x <- model.matrix(COVID ~ ., data = df[-train,])[, -1] # test data
probabilities <- predict(lasso_model_best, newx = x, type = "response")

# threshold = 0.5
predicted_classes <- ifelse(probabilities > 0.5, 1, 0) 

# confusion matrix
table(Actual = df[-train,]$COVID, Predicted = predicted_classes)
##       Predicted
## Actual   0   1
##      0  26   7
##      1   9 150
cat('test error rate:', mean(df[-train,]$COVID != predicted_classes))
## test error rate: 0.08333333

Change threshold to see different result.
